SIMPLE: fret
RECORDS: 8

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw> <pr>(fr⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<def>See 1st <er>Frith</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw> <pr>(fr⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fretted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fretting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>freten</ets> to eat,
consume; AS. <ets>fretan</ets>, for <ets>foretan</ets>; pref.
<ets>for-</ets> + <ets>etan</ets> to eat; akin to D. <ets>vreten</ets>,
OHG. <ets>frezzan</ets>, G. <ets>fressen</ets>, Sw.
<ets>fr⟦aum⟧ta</ets>, Goth. <ets>fra-itan</ets>. See <er>For</er>, and
<er>Eat</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To devour.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sow <qex>frete</qex> the child right in the cradle.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rub; to wear away by friction; to chafe; to gall;
hence, to eat away; to gnaw; <as>as, to <ex>fret</ex> cloth; to fret a
piece of gold or other metal; a worm <ex>frets</ex> the plants of a
ship.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With many a curve my banks I <qex>fret</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To impair; to wear away; to diminish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By starts⟦br⟧
His <qex>fretted</qex> fortunes give him hope and fear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make rough, agitate, or disturb; to cause to
ripple; <as>as, to <ex>fret</ex> the surface of water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To tease; to irritate; to vex.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fret</qex> not thyself because of evil doers.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xxxvii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be worn away; to
chafe; to fray; <as>as, a wristband <ex>frets</ex> on the
edges</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To eat in; to make way by corrosion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many wheals arose, and <qex>fretted</qex> one into another with
great excoriation.</q> <rj><qau>Wiseman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be agitated; to be in violent commotion; to
rankle; <as>as, rancor <ex>frets</ex> in the malignant
breast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be vexed; to be chafed or irritated; to be angry;
to utter peevish expressions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>frets</qex>, he fumes, he stares, he stamps the
ground.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The agitation of the
surface of a fluid by fermentation or other cause; a rippling on the
surface of water.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Agitation of mind marked by complaint and
impatience; disturbance of temper; irritation; <as>as, he keeps his mind
in a continual <ex>fret</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet then did Dennis rave in furious <qex>fret</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Herpes; tetter.</def>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The worn sides
of river banks, where ores, or stones containing them, accumulate by
being washed down from the hills, and thus indicate to the miners the
locality of the veins.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fretten</ets> to adorn,
AS. <ets>fr⟦ae⟧twan</ets>, <ets>fr⟦ae⟧twian</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>fratah⟦omac⟧n</ets>, cf. Goth. <ets>us-fratwjan</ets> to make wise,
also AS. <ets>fr⟦ae⟧twe</ets> ornaments, OS. <ets>fratah⟦imac⟧</ets>
adornment.]</ety> <def>To ornament with raised work; to variegate; to
diversify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Whose skirt with gold was <qex>fretted</qex> all about.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yon gray lines,⟦br⟧
That <qex>fret</qex> the clouds, are messengers of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ornamental work in relief,
as carving or embossing. See <er>Fretwork</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An ornament consisting of small
fillets or slats intersecting each other or bent at right angles, as in
classical designs, or at oblique angles, as often in Oriental
art.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His lady's cabinet is a adorned on the <qex>fret</qex>, ceiling,
and chimney-piece with . . . carving.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 596 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The reticulated headdress or net, made of gold or
silver wire, in which ladies in the Middle Ages confined their
hair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>fret</qex> of gold she had next her hair.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fret saw</b></col>, <cd>a saw with a long, narrow blade,
used in cutting frets, scrolls, etc.; a scroll saw; a keyhole saw; a
compass saw.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>frette</ets> a
saltire, also a hoop, ferrule, prob. a dim. of L. <ets>ferrum</ets>
iron. For sense 2, cf. also E. <ets>fret</ets> to rub.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A saltire interlaced with a
mascle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A short piece of wire, or other
material fixed across the finger board of a guitar or a similar
instrument, to indicate where the finger is to be placed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: Fret
<hw>Fret</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To furnish with frets, as an
instrument of music.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fretful</ent>⟦br⟧
